Convolutional Neural Networks¶

Project: Write an Algorithm for a Dog Identification App¶

Why We're Here¶

As part of Udacity online course on Deep Learning, this notebook is my first 'hands-on' exercise to use convolutionnal neural networks to classify images.

I'm tackling the very classic problem of dog classification. The goal is to build a model capable of doing breed classification of a dog by just “looking” into its image.

If a dog is detected in the image, the app should provide an estimate of the dog's breed. If it's a human, it will provide an estimate of the dog breed that is most resembling.

In this real-world setting, I needed to piece together a series of models to perform different tasks; for instance, the algorithm that detects humans in an image will be different from the CNN that infers dog breed.

Log Book¶

Let's describe this journey.

I learned that the practice is far ahead of the theory in deep learning :)

First, I tried to build a CNN from scratch. This model had to learn how to see by seeing only a few dog images. I experimented with many (many!!) different architectures... My main trouble was OVERFITTING. Indeed, with only 64 sample images from 133 classes, my from scratch model had difficulties to generalize. I took me hours of litterature reading, to handle overfitting, nights of training to test hyperparameters, almost drove me crazy not to do better than 35%! I conclueded, that one cannot properly learn how to see if it only sees dogs!

Then, using transfer learning, I could take advantage of a model already sees, ie. recognizes patterns, textures, colors... and I only neeeded to teach him how to recognize dog breeds. With the very same sets preparation, it took me about half an hour to choose and implement the model, trained it for only 5 epochs and get >80% accuaracy.

Take away¶

If I were to build a model from scratch, I'll certainly be carefull on the followings, that helped me fight against overfitting:

  • Dropout: remove activations at random during training in order to regularize the model
  • Data augmentation: modify model inputs during training in order to effectively increase data size
  • Batch normalization : adjust the parameterization of a model in order to make the loss surface smoother
  • Residual: As explained in fast.ai course, this trick has been discovered by chance and improved my performances, as it did it the imagenet dataset (https://arxiv.org/pdf/1512.03385.pdf)
  • Optimizer & Batch size: I first added a momentum on my SGD optimizer, to accelerate the training, but I had trouble to adjust together (batch size, learning rate, momentum). I then readed about Adam Optimizer that is adaptative, which indeed was easyer to use. Also, I started with batch size of 64, but the variability on losses across epochs was large, as if the model learned too much before validation check, so I decreased batch size to 20. Something that would worse testing that would be instead of Adam, try Optimgrad or SGD with nesterov momentum (need to choose parameters).

def show_dataset(dataset, n_edition=6, n_image=3, title=''):
    plt.figure()
    idx = np.arange(len(dataset))
    np.random.shuffle(idx)
    img = np.vstack((np.hstack((np.asarray(dataset[idx[i]][0]) for _ in range(n_edition)))
                   for i in range(n_image)))
    plt.imshow(img)
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.title(title, fontsize=30)

def show_image(img, title=None, ax=None, resize=None):
    if isinstance(img, str):
        img = cv2.imread(img)
    elif not isinstance(img, np.ndarray):
        raise ValueError('img should be of a path or an array. ') 
    if resize is not None: 
        img = cv2.resize(img, resize)   
    cv_rgb = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)
    plt.imshow(cv_rgb)
    if title is not None:
        plt.title(title)

Step 1: Detect Humans¶

In this section, we use OpenCV's implementation of Haar feature-based cascade classifiers to detect human faces in images.

OpenCV provides many pre-trained face detectors, stored as XML files on github. We have downloaded one of these detectors and stored it in the haarcascades directory. In the next code cell, we demonstrate how to use this detector to find human faces in a sample image.

In [5]:
import cv2                
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt                        
%matplotlib inline                               

# extract pre-trained face detector
face_cascade = cv2.CascadeClassifier('haarcascades/haarcascade_frontalface_alt.xml')

# load color (BGR) image
img = cv2.imread(human_files[15])
# convert BGR image to grayscale
gray = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)

# find faces in image by executing
# the classifier stored in `face_cascade`, that 
# takes the grayscale image as a parameter.  
faces = face_cascade.detectMultiScale(gray)

# print number of faces detected in the image
print('Number of faces detected:', len(faces))

# get bounding box for each detected face
for (x,y,w,h) in faces:
    # add bounding box to color image
    cv2.rectangle(img,(x,y),(x+w,y+h),(255,0,0),2)
    
# convert BGR image to RGB for plotting
cv_rgb = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)

# display the image, along with bounding box
plt.imshow(cv_rgb)
plt.show()

Number of faces detected: 1

Before using any of the face detectors, it is standard procedure to convert the images to grayscale. The detectMultiScale function executes the classifier stored in face_cascade and takes the grayscale image as a parameter.

In the above code, faces is a numpy array of detected faces, where each row corresponds to a detected face. Each detected face is a 1D array with four entries that specifies the bounding box of the detected face. The first two entries in the array (extracted in the above code as x and y) specify the horizontal and vertical positions of the top left corner of the bounding box. The last two entries in the array (extracted here as w and h) specify the width and height of the box.

Write a Human Face Detector¶

We use this procedure to write a function that returns True if a human face is detected in an image and False otherwise.

In [6]:
def face_detector(img_path):
    """Returns "True" if face is detected in image stored at img_path   
        Args:
            img_path (str):  file path to an image
        Returns:
            Bool: `True` if a human face is detected in an image and `False` otherwise. 
    """
    img = cv2.imread(img_path)
    gray = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
    faces = face_cascade.detectMultiScale(gray)
    return len(faces) > 0

In [8]:
import torch
import torchvision.models as models

# define VGG16 model
VGG16 = models.vgg16(pretrained=True)

# check if CUDA is available
use_cuda = torch.cuda.is_available()

# move model to GPU if CUDA is available
if use_cuda:
    VGG16 = VGG16.cuda()

Given an image, this pre-trained VGG-16 model returns a prediction (derived from the 1000 possible categories in ImageNet) for the object that is contained in the image.

Making Predictions with a Pre-trained Model¶

In the next code cell, we will write a function that accepts a path to an image (such as 'dogImages/train/001.Affenpinscher/Affenpinscher_00001.jpg') as input and returns the index corresponding to the ImageNet class that is predicted by the pre-trained VGG-16 model.

We go read how to appropriately pre-process tensors for this pre-trained VGG models in the PyTorch documentation. It's said:

During training, the input to our ConvNets is a fixed-size 224 × 224 RGB image. The only preprocessing we do is subtracting the mean RGB value, computed on the training set, from each pixel.

We download class labels used when training VGG as json have been downloaded from: https://s3.amazonaws.com/outcome-blog/imagenet/labels.json and saved it in ./data/imagenet_labels.json.

In [9]:
from PIL import Image
import requests
import io
import json
from torch.autograd import Variable
import torchvision.models as models
import torchvision.transforms as transforms
import torch.nn as nn

vgg16_transforms = transforms.Compose([transforms.Resize((224, 224)),
                                             transforms.ToTensor(),
                                             transforms.Normalize(mean=[0.485, 0.456, 0.406],
                                                                  std=[0.229, 0.224, 0.225])])

with open('data/imagenet_labels.json') as json_data:
    labels = json.load(json_data)
imagenet_labels = {int(key): value for key, value in labels.items()}

def VGG16_predict(img_path, verbose=False):
    '''
    Use pre-trained VGG-16 model to obtain index corresponding to 
    predicted ImageNet class for image at specified path
    
    Args:
        img_path (str): path to an image
        verbose (bool): if True, print out results. 
    Returns:
        Index corresponding to VGG-16 model's prediction
    '''
    
    # Load the image from the given img_path
    img = Image.open(img_path)  # Read bytes and store as an img.
    # Pre-process the image and convert it to a tensor
    img = vgg16_transforms(img)
    # Unsqueeze inserts a new axis, to convert format (num color channels, height, width) to (num input imgs, num color channels, height, width).
    img = img.unsqueeze(0)  # Insert the new axis at index 0 i.e. in front of the other axes/dims. 
    # Pytorch pretrained model expects Variable as inputs
    img = Variable(img)
    # Get probability from VGG output  
    m = nn.Softmax()
    prediction = m(VGG16(img))  # Returns a Tensor of shape (batch, num class labels)
    precision = prediction.data.numpy().max()*100  # Our precision is defined as softmax probability x 100
    max_prediction = prediction.data.numpy().argmax()  # Our prediction will be the index of the class label with the largest value.
    if verbose:
        label = imagenet_labels[max_prediction]
        print(f'VGG predicted {label} with precision %.2f%% percent' %precision)  # Converts the index to a string using our labels dict
        show_image(img_path, title=label) 
    # Return the *index* of the predicted class for that image
    return max_prediction # predicted class index

Write a Dog Detector¶

While looking at the dictionary, we notice that the categories corresponding to dogs appear in an uninterrupted sequence and correspond to dictionary keys 151-268, inclusive, to include all categories from 'Chihuahua' to 'Mexican hairless'. Thus, in order to check to see if an image is predicted to contain a dog by the pre-trained VGG-16 model, we need only check if the pre-trained model predicts an index between 151 and 268 (inclusive).

Use these ideas to complete the dog_detector function below, which returns True if a dog is detected in an image (and False if not).

In [11]:
dog_index = np.arange(151,269) 
def dog_detector(img_path, verbose=False):
    """Returns "True" if a dog is detected in an image stored at img_path   
        Args:
            img_path (str):  file path to an image
        Returns:
            Bool: `True` if a dog is detected in an image and `False` otherwise. 
    """
    predict_index = VGG16_predict(img_path, verbose)  # Our prediction will be the index of the class label with the largest value.
    return predict_index in dog_index

Step 3: Create a CNN to Classify Dog Breeds (from Scratch)¶
Now that we have functions for detecting humans and dogs in images, we need a way to predict breed from images.  In this step, we will create a CNN that classifies dog breeds.


We must create our CNN from scratch (so, we can't use transfer learning yet!), and we must attain a test accuracy of at least 10%.  In Step 4 of this notebook, you will have the opportunity to use transfer learning to create a CNN that attains greatly improved accuracy.


We mention that the task of assigning breed to dogs from images is considered exceptionally challenging.  To see why, consider that even a human would have trouble distinguishing between a Brittany and a Welsh Springer Spaniel.





Brittany
Welsh Springer Spaniel














It is not difficult to find other dog breed pairs with minimal inter-class variation (for instance, Curly-Coated Retrievers and American Water Spaniels).


We also mention that random chance presents an exceptionally low bar: setting aside the fact that the classes are slightly imabalanced, a random guess will provide a correct answer roughly 1 in 133 times, which corresponds to an accuracy of less than 1%.

Question 3: Describe your chosen procedure for preprocessing the data.


    

  • How does my code resize and prepare the images?
    • 

  • Did you decide to augment the dataset?  If so, how (through translations, flips, rotations, etc)?  If not, why not?
    • 



Answer:


    

  • On image resizing:
      

    • The images have various sizes, but the model can handle only one, so we take the size of (MEAN - STD) for all, to ensure that 83% of the are initially bigger. This leads us to a dimension around 220 pixels, so, while we are at it, we chose 224 pixels just like pretrained-models (to then be able to compare the training without adding any unknown factor/difference on the loader). 
      • 

    • I chose to crope and resize my images in format (224x224). I chose to crope instead of stretching to ensure that my images would not be distorted. 
      • 

    • I kept RGB colors because my model needed to be able to learn dog's coat colour. I kept the RGB normalization used in the imagenet datasets, to kind of 'zscore' my three colour channels, because I thought the distribution of R, G, B remained the same across the datasets (imagenet also contains dog images). 
      • 

    

    

    • 

  • On data augmentation 
      

    • Looking at this very cool fast.ai course video, they say data-augmentation is a key point to avoid overfitting, and describe it as 'new data for free'.  They even go further by suggesting that, if one tackles new computer vision challenges, data-augmentation should be one of the first reasearch question to tackle!
      • 

    • The purpose of those transforms is to augment the training data with plausible transformation only. Indeed, we don't want the model to learn on dogs with their head down or on green-looking. Hence, I chose very basic transformations: 
        

      • very light color jitter
        • 

      • horizontal flip
        • 

      • small random rotations
        • 

      

      • 

    • I chose to augment only the training data, insofar as we want to ensure our model learns to recognize dog breeds at all, and  not transformed dogs! Furthermore, I shuffle the training data, to make sure many each learning session (batch) contains different breed to learn/compare with one another.

# check if CUDA is available
use_cuda = torch.cuda.is_available()
device = torch.device("cuda:0" if use_cuda else "cpu")

resize = [
          # Resize the input PIL Image to the given size.
          transforms.Resize(224),
          # Crops the given PIL Image at the center.
          transforms.CenterCrop(224)]

to_tensor = [             
              # Convert imagee to tensor
              transforms.ToTensor(),
              # Normalize the tensor image with mean and standard deviation
              # Here, mean and std are taken from imagenet database, so we 
              # kind of 'zscore' our data in R, G, B dimensions.  
              transforms.Normalize(mean=[0.485, 0.456, 0.406],
                                   std=[0.229, 0.224, 0.225])]

image_augmentation = [
                      transforms.ColorJitter(hue=.1, saturation=.1),
                      transforms.RandomRotation((-40,40)),
                      transforms.RandomHorizontalFlip()]

scratch_transforms = {
    'train': transforms.Compose(resize + image_augmentation + to_tensor) , 
    'valid': transforms.Compose(resize + to_tensor) , 
    'test': transforms.Compose(resize + to_tensor)
             }

image_folders = {folder: datasets.ImageFolder(f'{ConfigPath.dogs}/{folder}/', 
                          transform=scratch_transforms[folder])
                 for folder in ['train', 'valid', 'test']}

def get_loaders(batch_size, **kwargs):
    return {folder: torch.utils.data.DataLoader(image_folders[folder], 
                                                       # shuffle only train data
                                                       shuffle=folder=='train', 
                                                        batch_size=batch_size,
                                                       **kwargs)
                 for folder in ['train', 'valid', 'test']}
loaders_scratch = get_loaders(batch_size=20, num_workers=0)

Model Architecture¶
Define helpers to avoid repeting always the same lines of code when defining the network.


In the cell bellow, I buid helpers to design a convolutionnal layer. Based on the litterature I read, and advices from experienced people, I tested different type of layers, from the simplest to the complex:


    

  • basic: (Conv2d, ReLu activation) 
    • 

  • with batch norm: (Conv2d, Batch norm 2d,  ReLu activation)
    • 

  • with batch norm and residual (using short-cuts to jump over some layers): 
(Conv2d, ResBlock with batch norm,  ReLu activation)
    • 



Each convolution has the following parameters:


    

  • ni: nb of inputs
    • 

  • nf: nb of outputs
    • 

  • downsampling_method: stride or maxpool
    • 

  • kernel_size: size of filter
    • 














In [19]:



    


import torch.nn as nn
def Conv2d(ni,nf, downsampling_method='stride', downsampling_factor=2, kernel_size=3): 
    if downsampling_method == 'stride':
        return nn.Conv2d(ni, nf, kernel_size=kernel_size, stride=downsampling_factor, padding=1)
    elif  downsampling_method == 'maxpool':
        return nn.Sequential(Conv2d(ni, nf, kernel_size=kernel_size, stride=1, padding=1), 
                             nn.MaxPool2d(downsampling_factor, downsampling_factor))
    else: # downsampling_method == 'avgpool'
        return nn.Sequential(Conv2d(ni, nf, kernel_size=3, stride=1, padding=1), 
                             nn.AvgPool2d(downsampling_factor, downsampling_factor)) 
    
# basic convolutional layer (no normalization)
def ConvLayer_basic(ni, nf, downsampling_method='stride', downsampling_factor=2, kernel_size=3): 
    return nn.Sequential(Conv2d(ni, nf, downsampling_method, downsampling_factor, kernel_size=kernel_size), 
                         nn.ReLU())
                                                                                         
# convolutional layer with batch normalization 2d
def ConvLayer_bnorm(ni,nf, downsampling_method='stride', downsampling_factor=2, kernel_size=3): 
    return nn.Sequential(
           Conv2d(ni, nf, downsampling_method, downsampling_factor, kernel_size=kernel_size),   
           nn.BatchNorm2d(nf),
           nn.ReLU())
                                                 
def LinearLayer_basic(in_features, out_features):
    return nn.Sequential(nn.Linear(in_features, out_features), 
                      nn.ReLU())                                       

def LinearLayer_bnorm(in_features, out_features):
    return nn.Sequential(nn.Linear(in_features, out_features), 
                      nn.BatchNorm1d(out_features), 
                      nn.ReLU())    

# convolutional layer with batch normalization 2d and Resnet-ish
class ResBlock(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, nf):
        super().__init__()
        self.conv1 = ConvLayer_bnorm(nf,nf, downsampling_factor=1)
        self.conv2 = ConvLayer_bnorm(nf,nf, downsampling_factor=1)
        
    def forward(self, x): 
        return x + self.conv2(self.conv1(x))
    
def ConvLayer_residual(ni,nf, downsampling_method='stride', downsampling_factor=2, kernel_size=3): 
    return  nn.Sequential(Conv2d(ni, nf, downsampling_method, downsampling_factor, kernel_size),   
            ResBlock(nf),                    
            nn.ReLU())

import torch.nn.functional as F
# set PIL to tolerate truncated images:
from PIL import ImageFile 
ImageFile.LOAD_TRUNCATED_IMAGES = True

# define the CNN architecture
class Net(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, input_size=[224, 224, 3], 
                 n_hidden_features_filters = [16, 32, 64, 64, 256, 512], 
                 n_hidden_features_kernel = [5, 3, 3, 3, 3, 3],
                 n_inputs_classifier = int(4*4*512), 
                 n_hidden_classifier=1330, 
                 n_outputs_classifier=133, 
                 conv='basic',  
                 downsampling_factor=2, 
                 downsampling_method='stride', 
                 p_dropout=0.25):
        if conv == 'basic':
            conv_layer = ConvLayer_basic
            linear_layer = LinearLayer_basic
        elif conv == 'bnorm':
            conv_layer = ConvLayer_bnorm
            linear_layer = LinearLayer_bnorm
        else: # conv == 'residual'
            conv_layer = ConvLayer_residual
            linear_layer = LinearLayer_bnorm
        super(Net, self).__init__()
        
        # feature layers 
        self.features = [conv_layer(ni=input_size[2], nf=n_hidden_features_filters[0], kernel_size=n_hidden_features_kernel[0])]
        for k_feat in range(len(n_hidden_features_filters)-1):
            self.features.append(conv_layer(ni=n_hidden_features_filters[k_feat], 
                                            nf=n_hidden_features_filters[k_feat+1], 
                                            kernel_size=n_hidden_features_kernel[k_feat+1]))
        # classifier layers
        feature_size = [int(size/downsampling_factor**(len(n_hidden_features_filters))) for size in input_size]
        feature_deepness = n_hidden_features_filters[-1]
        
        
        self.avg_pool = nn.AvgPool2d(kernel_size=feature_size[0])
        
        if conv == 'basic':
            # no batch norm
            self.classifier0 = nn.Sequential(
                           nn.Linear(n_inputs_classifier, n_hidden_classifier), 
                           nn.ReLU())   
        else: 
            # with batch norm 
            self.classifier0 = nn.Sequential(
                           nn.Linear(n_inputs_classifier, n_hidden_classifier), 
                           nn.BatchNorm1d(n_hidden_classifier), 
                           nn.ReLU())   
        self.classifier1 = nn.Linear(in_features=n_hidden_classifier, out_features=n_outputs_classifier)
        
        # intialize classifier weights
        self.initialize_weights()    
        # dropout layer (p=0.25)
        self.dropout = nn.Dropout(p_dropout)
    def initialize_weights(self):
        for k_feat, feature in enumerate(self.features): 
            setattr(self, f'feature{k_feat}', feature)  
    def forward(self, x):
        # extract features
        for feature in self.features:
            x = feature(x)
            x = self.dropout(x)
    

        # flatten
        x = x.view(x.shape[0], -1)
        
        # classify 
        x = self.dropout(x)
        x = self.classifier0(x)
        x = self.dropout(x)
        x = self.classifier1(x)
        return x 
        

# create a complete CNN
model = Net()
print(model)

Question 4: Outline the steps you took to get to your final CNN architecture and your reasoning at each step.















Answer:


    

  • DAY1: I started with a very basic network with 3 convolutionnal layers and one fully connected layer with 133 outputs and a batch size of 60, SGD optimizer with a learning rate between 1e-4 and 1e-1 and no momentum. The model would not learn more than 5 epochs. I did not even run the test, but I am pretty sure it would have failed badly under 1%. 
    • 

  • DAY2 I added more layers, still with this basic CNN and got no improvments.
    • 

  • DAY3 From practice, back to the theory... I read a bunch of medium papers, looked at fast.ai courses and asked some advices around me. I learned that some medication against overfitting are: 
      

    • MORE DROPOUT
      • 

    • SLOWER LEARNING: decrease lr and/or batch size
      • 

    • BATCH NORMALISATION
So, I added dropout and batch normalisation. Because I was tired trying to custom learning rate and momentum together, I switched to ADAM optimizer, since it's adaptive (even id I also read that sometimes it's not very stable..). If I remember well, I went from like 5% to 15%. 
      • 

    

    • 

  • DAY4 More reading.... At that time I discover RESIDUAL BLOCK, that basicaly takes short-cuts to jump over some layers. On fast.ai video, the guy says 'whatever your computer vision problem, try to add Residual Block, it's always be better'. It convinced me 😊.
    • 

  • DAY5 More reading... And I heared about SIAMESE NETWORKS, that aree networks able to estimate the dissimilarity between two inputs. I tried out some code that I found, made to detect patterns in MNIST dataset, that I adapted to my problem. My siamese network could give a similarity rating on a pair of dog images, that (empirically) was not that bad. But when I tried to classify the training images by computing the similarity matrix to ALL the train dataset, it took like forever and didn't give very good results... I certainly neeed to refine my architecture, but I took so long to train and test that I did not pursued in that direction... I'll put the exploratory notebook in this repository though.
    • 

  • DAY6 back to DAY5 step, and cleanup the mess. Still, I'm a bit frustrated that my notebook cannot really learn and overfitts from the begining (validation losses order of magnitude is way greater than training losses). Maybe I should have added some more dogs, or some more images at all... 
    •

import sys
from tqdm import tqdm 
from livelossplot import PlotLosses


def train(n_epochs, loaders, model, optimizer, criterion, use_cuda, save_path, 
          preload=False, max_successive_increasing_valid_loss=15):
    """returns trained model"""
    if save_path is not None: 
        valid_loss_path = save_path.replace('.pt', '_valid_loss.csv')
        train_loss_path = save_path.replace('.pt', '_train_loss.csv')
    
    losses = {'train':[], 'valid':[]}

    # initialize tracker for minimum validation loss
    valid_loss_min = np.Inf 
    if preload and save_path is not None: 
        try: 
            model.load_state_dict(torch.load(save_path))
            losses['valid'] = list(pd.read_csv(valid_loss_path))
            losses['train'] = list(pd.read_csv(train_loss_path))
            valid_loss_min = min(losses['valid'])
            
        except FileNotFoundError: 
            print(f'Could not find file {save_path}. \n Hence, could not load model state. \n Training from scratch. ')
            
    successive_increasing_valid_loss = 0 
    for epoch in range(1, n_epochs+1):
        # initialize variables to monitor training and validation loss
        train_loss = 0.0
        valid_loss = 0.0
        ###################
        # train the model #
        ###################
        model.train()
        batch_count_train = 0 
        for batch_idx, (data, target) in enumerate(loaders['train']):
            # move tensors to GPU if CUDA is available
            if use_cuda:
                data, target = data.cuda(), target.cuda()
            # clear the gradients of all optimized variables
            optimizer.zero_grad()
            # forward pass: compute predicted outputs by passing inputs to the model
            output = model(data)
            # calculate the batch loss
            loss = criterion(output, target)
            # backward pass: compute gradient of the loss with respect to model parameters
            loss.backward()
            # perform a single optimization step (parameter update)
            optimizer.step()
            # update training loss            
            train_loss += ((1 / (batch_idx + 1)) * (loss.data - train_loss))
            batch_count_train +=1 
            if not batch_count_train%50:  # print every 50 train batch
                print(f'Batch {batch_count_train} \tTrain Loss: {(train_loss/batch_count_train):.6f}') 
        losses['train'].append(train_loss/batch_count_train)
        if save_path is not None: 
            np.savetxt(train_loss_path, np.array(losses['train']))

        ######################    
        # validate the model #
        ######################
        model.eval()
        with torch.no_grad():
            batch_count_valid = 0
            for batch_idx, (data, target) in enumerate(loaders['valid']):
                # move to GPU
                if use_cuda:
                    data, target = data.cuda(), target.cuda()
                ## update the average validation loss
                # forward pass: compute predicted outputs by passing inputs to the model
                output = model(data)
                # calculate the batch loss
                loss = criterion(output, target)
                # update average validation loss 
                valid_loss += ((1 / (batch_idx + 1)) * (loss.data - valid_loss))
                batch_count_valid+=1
                if not batch_count_valid%10: # print every 10 valid batch
                    print(f'Batch {batch_count_valid} \tValidation Loss: {(valid_loss/batch_count_valid):.6f}')
        losses['valid'].append(valid_loss/batch_count_valid)
        if save_path is not None: 
            np.savetxt(valid_loss_path, np.array(losses['valid']))
            
        # print training/validation statistics 
        print('Epoch: {} \tTraining Loss: {:.6f} \tValidation Loss: {:.6f}'.format(
            epoch, 
            train_loss/batch_count_train,
            valid_loss/batch_count_valid)
            )     
        
         # save model if validation loss has decreased
        if valid_loss < valid_loss_min:
            print('Validation loss decreased ({:.6f} --> {:.6f}).  Saving model ...'.format(
            valid_loss_min/batch_count_valid,
            valid_loss/batch_count_valid))
            if save_path is not None: 
                torch.save(model.state_dict(), save_path)
            valid_loss_min = valid_loss
            successive_increasing_valid_loss = 0 
        else: 
            successive_increasing_valid_loss += 1 
            if successive_increasing_valid_loss >=max_successive_increasing_valid_loss:
                # break training when overfitting starts
                return model, losses        
    # return trained model and losses
    return model, losses

def test(loaders, model, criterion, use_cuda):

    # monitor test loss and accuracy
    test_loss = 0.
    correct = 0.
    total = 0.

    model.eval()
    for batch_idx, (data, target) in enumerate(loaders['test']):
        # move to GPU
        if use_cuda:
            data, target = data.cuda(), target.cuda()
        # forward pass: compute predicted outputs by passing inputs to the model
        output = model(data)
        # calculate the loss
        loss = criterion(output, target)
        # update average test loss 
        test_loss = test_loss + ((1 / (batch_idx + 1)) * (loss.data - test_loss))
        # convert output probabilities to predicted class
        pred = output.data.max(1, keepdim=True)[1]
        # compare predictions to true label
        correct += np.sum(np.squeeze(pred.eq(target.data.view_as(pred))).cpu().numpy())
        total += data.size(0)
            
    print('Test Loss: {:.6f}\n'.format(test_loss))

    print('\nTest Accuracy: %2d%% (%2d/%2d)' % (
        100. * correct / total, correct, total))

I kept all feature extraction pre-trained pattern, that I frozed, and only adapted and trained the last layer to output 133 objects (breeds).

Predict Dog Breed with the Model¶
Write a function that takes an image path as input and returns the dog breed (Affenpinscher, Afghan hound, etc) that is predicted by your model.













In [35]:



    


def infer_breed_transfer(model, img_path):
    """ Predicts the dog breed that is predicted by the model """
    # load the image and return the predicted breed
    prepare_image = transforms.Compose([transforms.RandomResizedCrop(224),
                                        transforms.ToTensor(),
                                        transforms.Normalize(mean=[0.485, 0.456, 0.406],
                                                            std=[0.229, 0.224, 0.225])])
    m = torch.nn.Softmax()
    img = Image.open(img_path).convert('RGB')
    img = prepare_image(img).unsqueeze(0)
    if use_cuda:
        img = img.cuda()
    model.eval()
    output = model.forward(img)  # Returns a Tensor of shape (batch, num class labels)
    probs = m(output) # Convert score in probabilities 
    if use_cuda: #copy the tensor to host memory
        probs = probs.cpu()
    
    df = pd.DataFrame(data={'prob': probs.data.numpy().reshape(-1)*100, 'breed': dog_breeds})

    return df.sort_values(['prob'], ascending=False)

def predict_breed_transfer(img_path, model=None, verbose=False, infered=None):
    if infered is None: 
        infered=infer_breed_transfer(model, img_path)
    prediction = infered.iloc[0]
    precision = prediction.prob  # Our prediction will be the index of the class label with the largest value.    
    breed = prediction.breed  # Our prediction will be the index of the class label with the largest value.
    if verbose:
        print(f'Pretrained model predicted {breed} with precision %.2f %%.' % precision)  # Converts the index to a string using our labels dict
    return breed, precision # predicted class index

Step 7: Compare scratch and transfert models¶
In this last step, we visualize the network performances, to see where the model is right or wrong.
First, we show the confusion matrix for scratch and transfert model to evaluate specificity of the model.


Then we show in a barplot the misclassified pair of breeds and display the images of the first 5 misclassified pair of dogs.













In [39]:



    


from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix
@torch.no_grad()
def get_all_preds(model, loader):
    all_preds = torch.tensor([])
    for batch in loader:
        images, labels = batch
        preds = model(images)
        all_preds = torch.cat(
            (all_preds, preds)
            ,dim=0
        )
    return all_preds

def get_confusion_matrix(image_folder, model_preds):
    return confusion_matrix(image_folder.targets, model_preds.argmax(dim=1))

def get_misclass_df(image_folder, model_preds, labels=dog_breeds):
    df = pd.DataFrame(np.vstack([image_folder.targets, 
                                                   model_preds.argmax(dim=1)]).T, 
                                    columns=['actual', 'prediction'])
    df = df.applymap(lambda k: labels[k].split('.')[-1])
    df['count'] = 1
    misclass_df = df[df['actual'] != df['prediction']].groupby(['actual', 'prediction']).sum().sort_values(['count'], ascending=False).reset_index()
    misclass_df['pair'] = misclass_df['actual'] + ' / ' + misclass_df['prediction']
    return misclass_df

def get_performance(model, image_folder, loader, labels=dog_breeds): 
    preds = get_all_preds(model, loader)
    cm = get_confusion_matrix(image_folder, preds)
    misclass_df = get_misclass_df(image_folder, preds, labels)
    worst_misclass_df = misclass_df[['pair', 'count']].take(range(30))
    return cm, misclass_df, worst_misclass_df
